# t/recorded/mail-roundtrip.test — ring-2 outbound mail exchange (docs/13).
#
# A round-trip into käsi's own mailbox WITHOUT self-mail: the initiator is
# kasi+probe@decode.ee — a plus-addressed alias that is NOT käsi's own identity
# (reply-from is the bare kasi@decode.ee), so the SEV1 self-reply guard leaves it
# alone (decision-016), yet the reply still lands in the same real inbox (Fastmail
# subaddressing), so there is no external recipient and no third party. Run
# --ring live --record once and it captures BOTH cassettes: the real Claude turn
# (harness-run) AND the real Fastmail upload→import→submission exchange
# (mail-exchange). --ring recorded then replays both fully offline; sim scripts the
# turn and sends through SimMail. Portable across all three rings.

send allow-sender { address kasi+probe@decode.ee }

# Replies go out as a deliverable identity (SPF/DKIM/MX on decode.ee), not the
# <route>@kasi.test placeholder, so real recipients actually receive them.
send set-reply-from { address kasi@decode.ee }

deliver {
    from    kasi+probe@decode.ee
    to      kasi@decode.ee
    subject "roundtrip echo"
    body    "Write exactly the word DONE into out/reply.txt and nothing else. Do not ask any questions."
}

task 1 status is awaiting-agent

# Ring 1 scripts the turn; ring 2 replays the recorded one (block ignored).
agent {
    out reply.txt "DONE"
}

task 1 status is awaiting-user
outbound last from is kasi@decode.ee
outbound last to is kasi+probe@decode.ee
outbound last body matches "*DONE*"

# The bytes above are only what käsi assembled; assert the model recorded a real
# send — mark-email-sent fires only when Mail.Submit actually succeeded.
outbox last status is sent
